The Scottish tradition is wholly different from the
English -- dating back centuries, if not millennia.
Since Roman times (and probably earlier) there
has been no doubt about the differences. There
has been a border between the nations for that
long. Scots don't have the rigid English hierarchy,
that dates at least to the Conquest. Every Scot
thinks himself as good as any other. So their
attitude to education is quite different (as one
example -- if an important one). Likewise their
religious tradition is wholly different -- being one
that rejects established or imposed authority.
The quality of education and the rates of literacy
in Scotland have been higher (if not much higher)
than in England since printing came in.

Such traditions, even if hard to define or prove,
are immensely important. It is very much more
difficult for members of the English working,
peasant, or lower-middle-classes to become
a professional, or an artist of any sort -- than
it is for any Scot.

