You have heard of Hadrian's Wall, I trust?

It is a fact that the territory we now call &quot;England
and Wales&quot; was colonised by Romans for hundreds
of years and what we now call &quot;Scotland&quot; was not.
And that most of the people living in Scotland are
descended from those living there then. It's also
likely that most of the people south of the border
are also descended from those living there then.

It may be arguable that traditions do not last that
long. I think that certain fundamental attitudes
probably do -- constantly maintained, of course,
by the physical nature of the country and the forms
of government, social structure, and types of
agriculture it allows. Large farms with plenty of
tillage under a fairly strong government could
exist for many generations in 'England' -- resulting
in a highly structured society. The rougher land
north of the Border, the harder climate, the difficult
communications and the presence of the
Highlands all meant that nothing like that was
possible.

I am merely making the point that there IS a
border, and that there has been one in that
place for as long as there have been records.
Most other borders (without a geographical
barrier) have been far more flexible or transient.
The people on either side of Hadrian's Wall are
quite different and see themselves as being
different. Alliances across the border have
been rare.

Paul.

